% You are an expert Python engineer. Your goal is to write the pdd/cli_detector.py module.

% Role & Scope
Detects and bootstraps agentic CLI harnesses (Claude CLI, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI) required for `pdd fix`, `pdd change`, `pdd bug`, and `pdd setup`. The primary entry point `detect_and_bootstrap_cli()` presents a numbered table of CLIs with install/key status, lets the user select one or more, and walks through installation and API key configuration for each. The legacy `detect_cli_tools()` function is preserved for backward compatibility.

% Requirements

1. Dataclass: `CliBootstrapResult` with fields `cli_name: str`, `provider: str`, `cli_path: str`, `api_key_configured: bool`, `skipped: bool` (default False). All strings default to empty.

2. Function: `detect_and_bootstrap_cli() -> List[CliBootstrapResult]` — Phase 1 entry point for `pdd setup`.
   a. Print a step banner via `_print_step_banner()` imported from `pdd.setup_tool`.
   b. Detect all three CLIs via `shutil.which()` with fallback to common paths (~/.local/bin, /usr/local/bin, /opt/homebrew/bin) and nvm node version directories.
   c. Provider mappings: anthropic->claude, google->gemini, openai->codex. Table order: Claude CLI, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI.
   d. Print a numbered selection table showing install status and credential status per CLI, with aligned columns. Credential status reports: API key set (green ✓), or stored OAuth/subscription login configured (green ✓), or no credentials (red ✗).
   e. Accept comma-separated numeric input (e.g. "1,3"). Default to best available (installed+any-credential > installed > Claude). Any credential includes either API key OR stored OAuth login. "q"/"n" returns a skipped result.
   f. For each selected CLI, process install/credential/test in sequence. On skip or failure of one CLI, continue to the next.
   g. Install step: prompt user, run `npm install -g ...` via subprocess if accepted. Check npm availability first.
   h. Credential step: skip entirely when the CLI already has a stored OAuth/subscription credential (`_has_provider_oauth(provider)` returns True for the corresponding location: anthropic from `~/.claude/.credentials.json` or `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/credentials.json` or macOS keychain `Claude Code-credentials` or `CLAUDE_CODE_OAUTH_TOKEN` env; google from `~/.gemini/oauth_creds.json`; openai from `~/.codex/auth.json`). Issue #813 round-9 hardening: the anthropic file check MUST parse the credentials JSON shape via `_claude_credentials_file_has_oauth(path)` and require `claudeAiOauth.accessToken` or `claudeAiOauth.refreshToken` (or top-level fallback) to be non-empty — a bare size check (`stat().st_size > 0`) false-positives on stale, corrupt, or logged-out files that still contain bytes but no usable token, then `pdd setup` skips the API-key prompt and leaves the user with no working credential. The shape parse must swallow `OSError` and `JSONDecodeError` and return False. Match the parse style of the google/openai branches (they already parse for `refresh_token`/`access_token` and `token`/`tokens`/`OPENAI_API_KEY` respectively). Issue #813 root: prompting OAuth-only users for an API key here pushes them into the exact stale-key workflow this fix exists to make safe. When OAuth is detected without an API key, print a green confirmation that the OAuth credential will be used (for anthropic, also mention `PDD_KEEP_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=1` as the opt-out for forcing API-key billing). Only when neither API key nor OAuth is present, prompt for an API key, save to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` with shell-appropriate syntax, add source line to RC file, set in `os.environ`.
   i. CLI test step (always runs, cannot be skipped): run `cli --version`, fall back to `--help` if that fails.
   j. Handle KeyboardInterrupt/EOFError at every input prompt gracefully.
   k. Return list of results; if empty, return `[CliBootstrapResult(skipped=True)]`.

3. Function: `detect_cli_tools() -> None` — legacy detection. For each CLI: show found/not-found status, cross-reference API keys, offer installation for missing CLIs that have matching keys.

4. Shell detection: detect from `SHELL` env var (default "bash"). Map to RC file: zsh->.zshrc, bash->.bashrc, fish->~/.config/fish/config.fish.

5. API key file management: create `~/.pdd/` if needed. Write keys to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` (append, dedup by key name using regex). Add source line to RC file if not present. Shell syntax: bash/zsh use `export K=V`, fish uses `set -gx K V`. Source syntax: bash/zsh use `source path`, fish uses `test -f path ; and source path`.

6. Google provider: primary env var is GEMINI_API_KEY (used by Gemini CLI for AI Studio auth). Fallback is GOOGLE_API_KEY (Vertex AI convention). Check GEMINI_API_KEY first, then GOOGLE_API_KEY. Primary key for saving is GEMINI_API_KEY. Display whichever is actually set.

7. Module-level constants: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY`, `PROVIDER_DISPLAY`, `CLI_PREFERENCE`, `SHELL_RC_MAP` exposed for use by other modules.

% Dependencies

